introduction.p:
In a right triangle, with C = 90\degree, the Pythagorean theorem tells us that
c^{2} = a^{2} + b^{2}
If we allow angle C to vary, but keep a and b the same length, the side c will grow or shrink, depending on whether we increase or decrease the angle C, as shown below.

subsection.p:
\begin{align*}
                \dfrac{\sin A}{a} \amp = \dfrac{\sin C}{c} \amp\amp \text{Substitute the known values.}\\
                \dfrac{\sin A}{6} \amp = \dfrac{\sin 115.4\degree}{11} \amp\amp \text{Solve for} \sin A.\\
               \sin A \amp = 6 \cdot \dfrac{\sin 115.4\degree}{11} \approx 0.4928 \\
                \end{align*}

solution.p:
\begin{align*}
                b^{2} \amp = a^{2} + c^{2} - 2ac \cos B \amp\amp \text{Substitute the known values.}\\
                3^{2} \amp = 8^{2} + c^{2} - 2(8)c \cos 14.4\degree \amp\amp \text{Simplify.}\\
                9 \amp = 64 + c^{2} - 16c (0.9686)  \amp\amp \text{Write the quadratic equation in standard form.} \\
                0 \amp = c^{2}-15.497c + 55 \amp\amp \text{Apply the quadratic formula.}\\
                \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
            c \amp = \dfrac{15.497 \pm \sqrt{(-15.497)^{2} - 4(1)(55)}}{2(1)} \amp\amp \text{Simplify.}\\
              \amp = \dfrac{15.497 \pm  4.490}{2} = 5.503~ \text{or}~ 9.994\\
              \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
               c^{2} \amp = a^{2} + b^{2} - 2ab \cos C \amp\amp \text{Substitute the known values.}\\
               5.503^{2} \amp = 8^{2} + 3^{2} - 2(8)(3) \cos C \amp\amp \text{Solve for} \cos C.\\
               \cos C \amp = \dfrac{5.503^{2} - 64 - 9}{-48} = 0.889876\\
               C \amp = \cos^{-1} 0.889876) = 27.1\degree \\
               \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
               c^{2} \amp = a^{2} + b^{2} - 2ab \cos C \amp\amp \text{Substitute the known values.}\\
               9.994^{2} \amp = 8^{2} + 3^{2} - 2(8)(3) \cos C \amp\amp \text{Solve for} \cos C.\\
               \cos C \amp = \dfrac{9.994^{2} - 64 - 9}{-48} = -0.560027\\
               C \amp = \cos^{-1} (-0.560027) = 124.1\degree \\
               \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
                b^{2} \amp = a^{2} + c^{2} - 2ac \cos B \amp\amp \text{Substitute the known values.}\\
                 \amp = 12^{2} + 18^{2} - 2(12)18 \cos 160\degree = 873.95\amp\amp \text{Take square roots.}\\
                b \amp = 29.56 \\
                \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
               a^{2} \amp = b^{2} + c^{2} - 2bc \cos A \amp\amp \text{Substitute the known values.}\\
               12^{2} \amp = 29.56^{2} + 18^{2} - 2(29.56)(18) \cos A \amp\amp \text{Solve for} \cos A.\\
               \cos A \amp = \dfrac{12^{2} - 29.56^{2} - 18^{2}}{-2(29.56)(18)} = 0.9903\\
               C \amp = \cos^{-1} (0.9903) = 8\degree \\
               \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
                \dfrac{\sin B}{6} \amp = \dfrac{\sin 40\degree}{10} \\
               \sin B \amp = 0.3857\\
                \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
                10^{2} \amp = 6^{2} + c^{2} - 2(6)c \cos 40\degree\\
               c^{2} - (12 \cos 40\degree)c - 64 \amp = 0 \\
               c \amp = \dfrac{12 \cos 40\degree \pm \sqrt{(-12 \cos 40\degree)^{2} - 4(1)(-64)}}{2(1)}
                \end{align*}
